**Project Overview**

A decentralized "elevator waiting-time" option platform where users trade CALL/PUT options based on predicted waiting time, settled with the custom PU token.
Implemented flow so far: create option -> writer deposits collateral -> buyer pays premium -> oracle records actual waiting time at expiry -> settlement by CALL/PUT rules -> writer retrieves collateral after grace period if not exercised.
A skeleton interface for "cancel and refund if unbought" is included.

**File Status and Completion**
- PrintToken.sol: Simplified ERC20 (PU) is complete. Includes controlled mint, transfer, approve/transferFrom, and test minting. Mostly stable.
- ElevatorOptionFactory.sol: Factory is implemented. It handles createOption, stores allOptions, and emits events. Possible additions: parameter bounds (duration/premium/collateral), creation fee/rate limit, admin transfer, batched queries.
- ElevatorOption.sol: Core option logic is a runnable baseline, not an empty scaffold.
  - Implemented: roles/params/state flags, events, deposit (writer collateral), buyOption (buyer premium), recordActualTime (oracle after expiry), exercise (CALL/PUT payout), retrieveExpired (writer retrieval after grace period).
  - Covered edge cases: repeated deposit, repeated buy, exercise before expiry, exercise before time recording, repeated exercise, timeout retrieval, etc.
  - Further hardening ideas: reentrancy protection, order cancellation (if unbought), oracle updates, richer event details, extreme-parameter checks, premium withdrawal/split strategy.
- elevatorOption.test.js: Hardhat test skeleton with flow comments and TODOs for both scenarios (CALL > threshold, PUT < threshold).

- Current contracts can run the base flow end-to-end: create -> deposit -> buyOption -> record actual time at expiry -> exercise / retrieveExpired.

**Remix/Hardhat/Truffle Usability**
- External function parameters are concise, and event coverage is suitable for frontend/script listeners.
- Suggested interaction order (demo script / Remix):
  1) Deploy PrintToken and mint test tokens to writer and buyer.
  2) Deploy Factory and call createOption (strike/premium/collateral/duration/type).
  3) Writer approves the new option contract, then calls deposit.
  4) Buyer approves, then calls buyOption.
  5) After expiry, oracle (factory deployer) calls recordActualTime.
  6) Buyer calls exercise; if no exercise and grace period passes, writer calls retrieveExpired.

**Team Split**
- A (core contract security / cancellation logic)
  - File: ElevatorOption.sol
  - Tasks:
    - Implement cancelIfUnbought (refund and finalize if unbought).
    - Harden require checks/reentrancy/parameter bounds; optionally add oracle update, inactive-timeout cancel, and premium split strategy.
  - Can run in parallel with B/C, but avoid simultaneous edits to the same file. If interface coordination with B is required, align first.
- B (factory and token strategy)
  - Files: ElevatorOptionFactory.sol, PrintToken.sol
  - Tasks:
    - Add creation fee/rate limit, duration/amount bounds, admin migration, and batched queries to factory.
    - Optionally add mint permissions/quotas or one-time airdrop to token.
  - Can run in parallel with A/C. If constructor or createOption interface changes, sync with A.
- C (tests and demo scripts)
  - File: elevatorOption.test.js
  - Tasks:
    - Complete CALL/PUT TODOs, assert balances/events/states, and add failure cases (exercise before expiry, before recording, repeated exercise, etc.).
    - Add cancelIfUnbought tests after A finishes; complete scripts and verify interactions in Remix/Hardhat/Truffle, then keep key runtime screenshots.
    - Finish README.
  - Can complete existing-flow tests independently first, then add new cases after interface stabilization.

Parallel recommendation: all three can proceed in parallel. If A/B modify shared interfaces (constructor params, events, function signatures), communicate first; C should add/adjust tests after interfaces are stable.